1
00:00:42,675 --> 00:00:44,446
(flames crackling)

2
00:00:47,446 --> 00:00:50,784
Reynolds has made my dreams
come true.

3
00:00:51,784 --> 00:00:55,156
And I have given him
what he desires most in return.

4
00:00:57,156 --> 00:00:59,528
MAN:
And what's that?

5
00:01:02,528 --> 00:01:04,762
Every piece of me.

6
00:01:07,299 --> 00:01:11,872
He's a very demanding man,
isn't he?

7
00:01:12,872 --> 00:01:15,874
Must be quite a challenge
to be with him.

8
00:01:15,875 --> 00:01:18,543
Yes.

9
00:01:18,544 --> 00:01:22,649
Maybe he's the most
demanding man.

10
00:01:23,649 --> 00:01:26,630
♪ ♪

11
00:01:37,630 --> 00:01:39,537
(sniffs)

12
00:01:44,537 --> 00:01:47,749
♪ ♪

13
00:01:56,749 --> 00:01:59,559
(birds chirping)

14
00:02:06,559 --> 00:02:09,514
♪ ♪

15
00:02:28,514 --> 00:02:30,681
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

16
00:02:30,682 --> 00:02:32,261
- Morning. -Morning.
- Morning.

17
00:02:42,261 --> 00:02:44,940
♪ ♪

18
00:02:54,940 --> 00:02:57,378
- Morning, ladies.
- Morning.

19
00:03:00,378 --> 00:03:02,447
- CYRIL: Morning.
- Morning, madam.

20
00:03:02,448 --> 00:03:04,293
CYRIL:
Good morning, ladies.

21
00:03:14,293 --> 00:03:16,571
♪ ♪

22
00:03:25,571 --> 00:03:26,937
Morning, Biddy.

23
00:03:26,938 --> 00:03:28,639
Morning, Mr. Woodcock.

24
00:03:28,640 --> 00:03:30,808
- Morning, Nana.
- Morning, Mr. Woodcock.

25
00:03:30,809 --> 00:03:33,847
- Pippa.
- Morning, sir.

26
00:03:34,847 --> 00:03:37,395
♪ ♪

27
00:03:50,395 --> 00:03:52,363
(clears throat softly)

28
00:03:52,364 --> 00:03:54,870
(quiet chatter)

29
00:03:57,870 --> 00:04:00,943
(sewing machine whirring nearby)

30
00:04:04,943 --> 00:04:07,821
♪ ♪

31
00:04:15,821 --> 00:04:17,858
Try these.

32
00:04:19,858 --> 00:04:21,926
Reynolds.

33
00:04:21,927 --> 00:04:24,629
They're delicious.

34
00:04:24,630 --> 00:04:27,398
Remember I told you, Johanna.

35
00:04:27,399 --> 00:04:30,368
No more stodgy things.

36
00:04:30,369 --> 00:04:31,835
(pen scratching on paper)

37
00:04:31,836 --> 00:04:33,807
I didn't know that.

38
00:04:35,807 --> 00:04:38,387
You may have told it
to someone else.

39
00:04:49,387 --> 00:04:50,588
CYRIL:
Morning.

40
00:04:50,589 --> 00:04:52,675
REYNOLDS:
Morning, my old so-and-so.

41
00:05:10,675 --> 00:05:13,111
Where have you gone, Reynolds?

42
00:05:13,112 --> 00:05:15,946
(pen scratching on paper)

43
00:05:15,947 --> 00:05:17,915
There's nothing I can say

44
00:05:17,916 --> 00:05:21,451
to get your attention
aimed back at me,

45
00:05:21,452 --> 00:05:23,858
is there?

46
00:05:25,858 --> 00:05:30,962
I cannot begin my day
with a confrontation, please.

47
00:05:30,963 --> 00:05:33,731
I'm delivering the dress today.

48
00:05:33,732 --> 00:05:36,967
And I can't take up space
with a confrontation.

49
00:05:36,968 --> 00:05:40,478
I simply don't have time
for confrontations.

50
00:05:47,478 --> 00:05:49,156
(pen scratching on paper)

51
00:05:57,156 --> 00:05:59,194
♪ ♪

52
00:06:03,194 --> 00:06:05,642
(door knocker tapping)

53
00:06:16,642 --> 00:06:18,176
Good morning, Countess.

54
00:06:18,177 --> 00:06:20,177
Good morning, Cyril.

55
00:06:20,178 --> 00:06:22,780
Good morning, Peter.

56
00:06:22,781 --> 00:06:24,726
(door closes)

57
00:06:34,726 --> 00:06:37,227
REYNOLDS:
Who's this beautiful stranger?

58
00:06:37,228 --> 00:06:38,763
(Countess chuckles softly)

59
00:06:38,764 --> 00:06:41,901
I need to see you
far more often, Henrietta.

60
00:06:42,901 --> 00:06:45,203
I am very excited.

61
00:06:45,204 --> 00:06:46,770
I am, too.

62
00:06:46,771 --> 00:06:48,079
Come in.

63
00:06:55,079 --> 00:06:57,709
♪ ♪

64
00:07:23,709 --> 00:07:25,906
CYRIL:
Exquisite.

65
00:07:53,906 --> 00:07:55,773
Yes?

66
00:07:55,774 --> 00:07:57,708
Let's take it for a walk.

67
00:07:57,709 --> 00:07:59,117
(Henrietta laughs)

68
00:08:05,117 --> 00:08:06,757
(Henrietta laughs)

69
00:08:11,757 --> 00:08:13,157
REYNOLDS:
Beautiful work, ladies.

70
00:08:13,158 --> 00:08:15,626
- Thank you very much. -Yes.
- Thank you. -Hear, hear.

71
00:08:15,627 --> 00:08:18,898
It's beautiful, Reynolds.

72
00:08:19,898 --> 00:08:22,937
Worth everything
we've been through.

73
00:08:24,937 --> 00:08:28,739
I feel like
it will give me courage.

74
00:08:28,740 --> 00:08:31,912
(low crowd chatter)

75
00:08:33,912 --> 00:08:36,157
♪ ♪

76
00:08:45,157 --> 00:08:47,157
MAN: Ladies and gentlemen,
take your seats, please.

77
00:08:54,066 --> 00:08:55,666
(low conversations)

78
00:08:55,667 --> 00:08:58,692
- Evening, Stephen. Is she here?
- Yes, sir.

79
00:09:21,692 --> 00:09:24,065
What do you want to do
about Johanna?

80
00:09:27,065 --> 00:09:31,236
I mean, she's lovely,
but the time has come.

81
00:09:32,236 --> 00:09:34,037
And she's getting fat,

82
00:09:34,038 --> 00:09:37,710
sitting around waiting for you
to fall in love with her again.

83
00:09:38,710 --> 00:09:40,378
(Reynolds sighs)

84
00:09:40,379 --> 00:09:43,383
I'll give her the October dress.

85
00:09:44,383 --> 00:09:45,383
If that's all right?

86
00:09:53,291 --> 00:09:55,792
I have an unsettled feeling.

87
00:09:55,793 --> 00:10:01,065
Based on... nothing
I can put my finger on.

88
00:10:01,066 --> 00:10:03,234
Just butterflies.

89
00:10:03,235 --> 00:10:07,705
Been having the strongest
memories of Mama lately,

90
00:10:07,706 --> 00:10:10,774
coming to me in my dreams.

91
00:10:10,775 --> 00:10:13,780
(sighs)
Smelling her scent.

92
00:10:15,780 --> 00:10:20,120
The strongest sense that...
she's near us.

93
00:10:22,120 --> 00:10:24,024
Reaching out towards us.

94
00:10:27,024 --> 00:10:30,130
I very much hope that she saw
the dress tonight. Don't you?

95
00:10:33,130 --> 00:10:35,032
Yes.

96
00:10:35,033 --> 00:10:37,768
It's comforting
to think the dead

97
00:10:37,769 --> 00:10:40,771
are watching over the living.

98
00:10:40,772 --> 00:10:43,846
I don't find that spooky at all.

99
00:10:48,846 --> 00:10:53,383
Why don't you go to the country
tonight?

100
00:10:53,384 --> 00:10:55,786
I'll follow tomorrow.

101
00:10:55,787 --> 00:10:58,791
Good idea.

102
00:10:59,791 --> 00:11:02,426
I like that idea very much.

103
00:11:02,427 --> 00:11:05,832
My old so-and-so.

104
00:11:07,832 --> 00:11:09,437
(softly):
Good.

105
00:11:12,437 --> 00:11:15,087
♪ ♪

106
00:11:30,087 --> 00:11:32,402
♪ ♪

107
00:11:44,402 --> 00:11:46,178
♪ ♪

108
00:11:53,178 --> 00:11:54,880
(knocking)

109
00:11:55,880 --> 00:11:58,249
Mr. Hansford?

110
00:11:58,250 --> 00:12:00,484
- Mr. Hansford?
- HANSFORD: Hello.

111
00:12:00,485 --> 00:12:02,519
- Good morning.
- Morning.

112
00:12:02,520 --> 00:12:04,488
- Fill it up, please.
- I will do.

113
00:12:04,489 --> 00:12:06,157
And check the oil and tires.

114
00:12:06,158 --> 00:12:08,392
Lovely. Thank you.

115
00:12:08,393 --> 00:12:09,826
(door closes)

116
00:12:09,827 --> 00:12:11,262
It's a hard frost this morning.

117
00:12:11,263 --> 00:12:13,464
It's cold, isn't it?
It's very bitter.

118
00:12:13,465 --> 00:12:16,979
(seabirds calling)

119
00:12:27,979 --> 00:12:30,884
(low conversations)

120
00:12:33,884 --> 00:12:36,495
♪ ♪

121
00:12:43,495 --> 00:12:46,566
(door swings open)

122
00:12:47,566 --> 00:12:50,033
- (loud thud)
- (grunts)

123
00:12:50,034 --> 00:12:52,839
(chuckles nervously)

124
00:12:53,839 --> 00:12:54,839
WOMAN:
Excuse me.

125
00:12:55,005 --> 00:12:56,574
Could we have a bit more toast,
please?

126
00:12:56,575 --> 00:12:58,956
Yes.

127
00:13:11,956 --> 00:13:13,990
WOMAN:
She's got it sorted?

128
00:13:13,991 --> 00:13:16,609
(women continue talking
indistinctly)

129
00:13:30,609 --> 00:13:32,343
Here you are.

130
00:13:32,344 --> 00:13:34,282
Thank you.

131
00:13:37,282 --> 00:13:39,350
Good morning.

132
00:13:39,351 --> 00:13:40,618
Morning.

133
00:13:40,619 --> 00:13:43,456
What would you like to order?

134
00:13:45,456 --> 00:13:47,291
(waitress clears throat)

135
00:13:47,292 --> 00:13:49,297
A Welsh rarebit.

136
00:13:52,297 --> 00:13:55,032
With a poached egg on top,
please.

137
00:13:55,033 --> 00:13:57,201
Not too runny.

138
00:13:57,202 --> 00:13:58,903
And bacon.

139
00:13:58,904 --> 00:14:00,970
Scones.

140
00:14:00,971 --> 00:14:05,375
Butter. Cream.

141
00:14:05,376 --> 00:14:07,478
Jam.

142
00:14:07,479 --> 00:14:09,116
Not strawberry.

143
00:14:12,116 --> 00:14:13,951
No?

144
00:14:13,952 --> 00:14:15,422
Raspberry?

145
00:14:17,422 --> 00:14:19,524
What else?

146
00:14:20,524 --> 00:14:21,691
Coffee or tea?

147
00:14:21,692 --> 00:14:24,394
Do you have Lapsang?

148
00:14:24,395 --> 00:14:26,297
I'll have a pot of Lapsang,
please.

149
00:14:26,298 --> 00:14:27,598
Good choice.

150
00:14:27,599 --> 00:14:29,936
And some sausages.

151
00:14:30,936 --> 00:14:33,509
And some sausages.

152
00:14:38,509 --> 00:14:40,019
Show me.

153
00:14:48,019 --> 00:14:50,387
Will you remember?

154
00:14:50,388 --> 00:14:52,690
Yes.

155
00:14:52,691 --> 00:14:53,957
(paper tearing)

156
00:14:53,958 --> 00:14:57,431
I'm keeping this.

157
00:14:59,431 --> 00:15:02,720
♪ ♪

158
00:15:21,720 --> 00:15:23,056
And now?

159
00:15:25,056 --> 00:15:27,260
Will you have dinner with me?

160
00:15:30,260 --> 00:15:32,376
Yes.

161
00:15:45,376 --> 00:15:47,610
<i>ALMA:
For the hungry boy.</i>

162
00:15:47,611 --> 00:15:49,671
<i>My name is Alma.</i>

163
00:16:13,671 --> 00:16:15,305
Am I late?

164
00:16:15,306 --> 00:16:16,306
No.

165
00:16:31,155 --> 00:16:33,134
(both laughing)

166
00:16:43,134 --> 00:16:45,437
What do you think?

167
00:16:46,437 --> 00:16:47,838
Mm.

168
00:16:47,839 --> 00:16:50,507
I like the sauce.

169
00:16:50,508 --> 00:16:52,714
Custard.

170
00:16:56,714 --> 00:16:58,816
It's quite good.

171
00:16:58,817 --> 00:17:00,656
Mm-hmm.

172
00:17:05,656 --> 00:17:08,861
May I, Alma?

173
00:17:09,861 --> 00:17:12,669
I like to see
who I'm talking to.

174
00:17:17,669 --> 00:17:20,241
Here.

175
00:17:24,241 --> 00:17:26,449
(Alma laughs softly)

176
00:17:31,449 --> 00:17:32,783
There you are.

177
00:17:32,784 --> 00:17:34,854
That's better.

178
00:17:35,854 --> 00:17:39,323
Does your mother
have brown eyes?

179
00:17:39,324 --> 00:17:41,158
Green.

180
00:17:41,159 --> 00:17:44,161
Do you look very much like her?

181
00:17:44,162 --> 00:17:46,363
I don't know. I think so.

182
00:17:46,364 --> 00:17:48,765
Do you have a photograph?

183
00:17:48,766 --> 00:17:50,767
Yes.

184
00:17:50,768 --> 00:17:52,335
Would you let me see it?

185
00:17:52,336 --> 00:17:55,208
Not here. At home.

186
00:17:57,208 --> 00:17:59,776
Carry it with you.

187
00:17:59,777 --> 00:18:03,683
Always carry her with you.

188
00:18:06,683 --> 00:18:08,751
Where's yours?

189
00:18:08,752 --> 00:18:10,220
Your mother.

190
00:18:10,221 --> 00:18:12,229
She's here in the canvas.

191
00:18:18,229 --> 00:18:21,565
- What do you mean?
- Hmm.

192
00:18:21,566 --> 00:18:25,404
You can sew almost anything
into the canvas of a coat.

193
00:18:27,404 --> 00:18:30,339
Secrets.

194
00:18:30,340 --> 00:18:35,679
Coins, words, little messages.

195
00:18:35,680 --> 00:18:38,382
When I was a boy,
I started to hide things

196
00:18:38,383 --> 00:18:41,418
in the linings of the garments,

197
00:18:41,419 --> 00:18:44,557
things that only I knew
were there.

198
00:18:45,557 --> 00:18:49,326
And over my breast, I have
a lock of my mother's hair,

199
00:18:49,327 --> 00:18:52,431
to keep her close to me always.

200
00:18:53,431 --> 00:18:55,298
She was quite
a remarkable woman.

201
00:18:55,299 --> 00:18:57,334
She taught me my trade.

202
00:18:57,335 --> 00:19:01,876
So I try to never be
without her.

203
00:19:05,876 --> 00:19:09,682
You must love her very much.

204
00:19:11,682 --> 00:19:14,635
♪ ♪

205
00:19:31,635 --> 00:19:34,270
- (door opens)
- REYNOLDS: Hello.

206
00:19:34,271 --> 00:19:35,572
This is Alma.

207
00:19:35,573 --> 00:19:37,240
- (dog whines)
- Say hello to Alma.

208
00:19:37,241 --> 00:19:38,441
- Hello.
- This is Alma.

209
00:19:38,442 --> 00:19:39,476
Come say hello to Alma.

210
00:19:39,477 --> 00:19:41,245
- Come on, come on.
- Hello.

211
00:19:41,246 --> 00:19:43,633
Shall we show her
the house, lads?

212
00:20:01,633 --> 00:20:04,800
<i>I made this dress for her
when I was 16 years old.</i>

213
00:20:04,801 --> 00:20:06,769
ALMA:
Beautiful.

214
00:20:06,770 --> 00:20:09,739
REYNOLDS: 'Twas for her second
husband, for the wedding.

215
00:20:09,740 --> 00:20:12,576
My father had died
many years before.

216
00:20:12,577 --> 00:20:16,345
Our nanny,
the evil Miss Blackwood...

217
00:20:16,346 --> 00:20:18,017
Black Death,
we used to call her...

218
00:20:19,017 --> 00:20:20,416
Because of superstition,

219
00:20:20,417 --> 00:20:22,486
she refused to help me
sew the dress,

220
00:20:22,487 --> 00:20:25,489
as she believed it would
bring her bad fortune,

221
00:20:25,490 --> 00:20:27,624
to never be a bride.

222
00:20:27,625 --> 00:20:29,625
Not that anyone
would've had her.

223
00:20:29,626 --> 00:20:31,361
And she seemed ancient to us.

224
00:20:31,362 --> 00:20:33,363
I have no idea
how old she actually was.

225
00:20:33,364 --> 00:20:36,333
And monstrously ugly.

226
00:20:36,334 --> 00:20:39,469
So I worked alone
for months and months,

227
00:20:39,470 --> 00:20:44,841
hunched over, sewing
and sweating and sewing.

228
00:20:44,842 --> 00:20:47,477
And the Black Death
never married anyway.

229
00:20:47,478 --> 00:20:49,746
All the help I could have had
from her.

230
00:20:49,747 --> 00:20:53,385
'Twas my sister, Cyril,
came to my rescue in the end.

231
00:20:55,385 --> 00:20:57,887
There are endless superstitions

232
00:20:57,888 --> 00:21:00,356
when making a wedding dress.

233
00:21:00,357 --> 00:21:01,991
Young girls afraid
they'll never marry

234
00:21:01,992 --> 00:21:03,527
if they touch one.

235
00:21:03,528 --> 00:21:06,997
Or models afraid
they'll marry only bald men

236
00:21:06,998 --> 00:21:09,836
- if they put one on.
- (Alma chuckles)

237
00:21:12,836 --> 00:21:15,409
And where's the dress now?

238
00:21:18,409 --> 00:21:20,876
I have no idea
what happened to it.

239
00:21:20,877 --> 00:21:22,412
No idea.

240
00:21:22,413 --> 00:21:25,382
Oh, most probably turned
to ashes by now,

241
00:21:25,383 --> 00:21:27,086
fallen to pieces.

242
00:21:29,086 --> 00:21:32,622
And your sister?

243
00:21:32,623 --> 00:21:33,623
What?

244
00:21:35,093 --> 00:21:37,661
Did she ever marry?

245
00:21:37,662 --> 00:21:39,829
No.

246
00:21:39,830 --> 00:21:43,100
Come on, boys,
let's have a fire.

247
00:21:43,101 --> 00:21:45,709
(flames crackling)

248
00:21:51,709 --> 00:21:53,817
(sighs)

249
00:22:00,817 --> 00:22:03,720
If you want to have
a staring contest with me,

250
00:22:03,721 --> 00:22:06,825
you will lose.

251
00:22:07,825 --> 00:22:10,662
Hmm.

252
00:22:11,662 --> 00:22:13,999
(chuckles)

253
00:22:14,999 --> 00:22:17,641
(chuckles softly)

254
00:22:23,641 --> 00:22:26,980
You are a very handsome man.

255
00:22:28,980 --> 00:22:32,020
You must be around
many beautiful women.

256
00:22:37,020 --> 00:22:39,959
Yes.

257
00:22:41,959 --> 00:22:44,193
So why are you not married?

258
00:22:44,194 --> 00:22:47,998
I make dresses.

259
00:22:47,999 --> 00:22:50,767
You cannot be married
when you make dresses?

260
00:22:50,768 --> 00:22:53,437
I'm certain
I was never meant to marry.

261
00:22:53,438 --> 00:22:55,142
I'm a confirmed bachelor.

262
00:22:58,142 --> 00:23:00,746
I'm incurable.

263
00:23:01,746 --> 00:23:03,882
Hmm.

264
00:23:04,882 --> 00:23:06,716
Marriage would
make me deceitful,

265
00:23:06,717 --> 00:23:09,522
and I don't ever want that.

266
00:23:12,522 --> 00:23:15,057
You sound so sure about things.

267
00:23:15,058 --> 00:23:16,832
I'm sure about that.

268
00:23:20,832 --> 00:23:25,067
I think you're only
acting strong.

269
00:23:25,068 --> 00:23:27,807
No, I am strong.

270
00:23:30,807 --> 00:23:31,975
For who?

271
00:23:31,976 --> 00:23:34,681
Not for me, I hope.

272
00:23:36,681 --> 00:23:41,518
I think it's the expectations
and assumptions of others

273
00:23:41,519 --> 00:23:43,663
that cause heartache.

274
00:23:52,663 --> 00:23:54,567
Would you help me
with something?

275
00:23:56,567 --> 00:23:58,616
- Yes.
- Come on.

